 = 1 * 2 * 4 = 8\np[1][1] = grid[0][0] * grid[0][1] * grid[1][0] = 1 * 2 * 3 = 6\nSo the answer is [[24,12],[8,6]].\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: grid = [[12345],[2],[1]]\nOutput: [[2],[0],[0]]\nExplanation: p[0][0] = grid[0][1] * grid[0][2] = 2 * 1 = 2.\np[0][1] = grid[0][0] * grid[0][2] = 12345 * 1 = 12345. 12345 % 12345 = 0. So p[0][1] = 0.\np[0][2] = grid[0][0] * grid[0][1] = 12345 * 2 = 24690. 24690 % 12345 = 0. So p[0][2] = 0.\nSo the answer is [[2],[0],[0]].\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= n == grid.length <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= m == grid[i].length <= 10⁵`\n\n- `2 <= n * m <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= grid[i][j] <= 10⁹`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/construct-product-matrix/","problemName":"Construct Product Matrix","problemNumber":2906,"problemSlug":"construct-product-matrix","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":2906,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Binary Indexed Tree","Segment Tree","Array"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Given the **0-indexed** arrays `prices` and `profits` of length `n`. There are `n` items in an store where the `i^(th)` item has a price of `prices[i]` and a profit of `profits[i]`.\n\nWe have to pick three items with the following condition:\n\n- `prices[i] < prices[j] < prices[k]` where `i < j < k`.\n\nIf we pick items with indices `i`, `j` and `k` satisfying the above condition, the profit would be `profits[i] + profits[j] + profits[k]`.\n\nReturn* the **maximum profit** we can get, and *`-1`* if it's not possible to pick three items with the given condition.*\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: prices = [10,2,3,4], profits = [100,2,7,10]\nOutput: 19\nExplanation: We can't pick the item with index i=0 since there are no indices j and k such that the condition holds.\nSo the only triplet we can pick, are the items with indices 1, 2 and 3 and it's a valid pick since prices[1] < prices[2] < prices[3].\nThe answer would be sum of their profits which is 2 + 7 + 10 = 19.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: prices = [1,2,3,4,5], profits = [1,5,3,4,6]\nOutput: 15\nExplanation: We can select any triplet of items since for each triplet of indices i, j and k such that i < j < k, the condition holds.\nTherefore the maximum profit we can get would be the 3 most profitable items which are indices 1, 3 and 4.\nThe answer would be sum of their profits which is 5 + 4 + 6 = 15.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: prices = [4,3,2,1], profits = [33,20,19,87]\nOutput: -1\nExplanation: We can't select any triplet of indices such that the condition holds, so we return -1.","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `3 <= prices.length == profits.length <= 2000`\n\n- `1 <= prices[i] <= 10⁶`\n\n- `1 <= profits[i] <= 10⁶`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Binary Indexed Tree","Segment Tree","Array"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"Given the **0-indexed** arrays `prices` and `profits` of length `n`. There are `n` items in an store where the `i^(th)` item has a price of `prices[i]` and a profit of `profits[i]`.\n\nWe have to pick three items with the following condition:\n\n- `prices[i] < prices[j] < prices[k]` where `i < j < k`.\n\nIf we pick items with indices `i`, `j` and `k` satisfying the above condition, the profit would be `profits[i] + profits[j] + profits[k]`.\n\nReturn* the **maximum profit** we can get, and *`-1`* if it's not possible to pick three items with the given condition.*\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: prices = [10,2,3,4], profits = [100,2,7,10]\nOutput: 19\nExplanation: We can't pick the item with index i=0 since there are no indices j and k such that the condition holds.\nSo the only triplet we can pick, are the items with indices 1, 2 and 3 and it's a valid pick since prices[1] < prices[2] < prices[3].\nThe answer would be sum of their profits which is 2 + 7 + 10 = 19.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: prices = [1,2,3,4,5], profits = [1,5,3,4,6]\nOutput: 15\nExplanation: We can select any triplet of items since for each triplet of indices i, j and k such that i < j < k, the condition holds.\nTherefore the maximum profit we can get would be the 3 most profitable items which are indices 1, 3 and 4.\nThe answer would be sum of their profits which is 5 + 4 + 6 = 15.\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: prices = [4,3,2,1], profits = [33,20,19,87]\nOutput: -1\nExplanation: We can't select any triplet of indices such that the condition holds, so we return -1.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `3 <= prices.length == profits.length <= 2000`\n\n- `1 <= prices[i] <= 10⁶`\n\n- `1 <= profits[i] <= 10⁶`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/maximum-profitable-triplets-with-increasing-prices-i/","problemName":"Maximum Profitable Triplets With Increasing Prices I","problemNumber":2907,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Given the **0-indexed** arrays `prices` and `profits` of length `n`. There are `n` items in an store where the `i^(th)` item has a price of `prices[i]` and a profit of `profits[i]`.\n\nWe have to pick three items with the following condition:\n\n- `prices[i] < prices[j] < prices[k]` where `i < j < k`.\n\nIf we pick items with indices `i`, `j` and `k` satisfying the above condition, the profit would be `profits[i] + profits[j] + profits[k]`.\n\nReturn* the **maximum profit** we can get, and *`-1`* if it's not possible to pick three items with the given condition.*\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: prices = [10,2,3,4], profits = [100,2,7,10]\nOutput: 19\nExplanation: We can't pick the item with index i=0 since there are no indices j and k such that the condition holds.\nSo the only triplet we can pick, are the