 array `[5, 3, 4, 6, 7]` to `[5, 6, 7]` which is strictly increasing.\n\nReturn *the total number of **incremovable** subarrays of* `nums`.\n\n**Note** that an empty array is considered strictly increasing.\n\nA **subarray** is a contiguous non-empty sequence of elements within an array.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: nums = [1,2,3,4]\nOutput: 10\nExplanation: The 10 incremovable subarrays are: [1], [2], [3], [4], [1,2], [2,3], [3,4], [1,2,3], [2,3,4], and [1,2,3,4], because on removing any one of these subarrays nums becomes strictly increasing. Note that you cannot select an empty subarray.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: nums = [6,5,7,8]\nOutput: 7\nExplanation: The 7 incremovable subarrays are: [5], [6], [5,7], [6,5], [5,7,8], [6,5,7] and [6,5,7,8].\nIt can be shown that there are only 7 incremovable subarrays in nums.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: nums = [8,7,6,6]\nOutput: 3\nExplanation: The 3 incremovable subarrays are: [8,7,6], [7,6,6], and [8,7,6,6]. Note that [8,7] is not an incremovable subarray because after removing [8,7] nums becomes [6,6], which is sorted in ascending order but not strictly increasing.","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= nums.length <= 50`\n\n- `1 <= nums[i] <= 50`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Two Pointers","Binary Search","Enumeration"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Easy","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"You are given a **0-indexed** array of **positive** integers `nums`.\n\nA subarray of `nums` is called **incremovable** if `nums` becomes **strictly increasing** on removing the subarray. For example, the subarray `[3, 4]` is an incremovable subarray of `[5, 3, 4, 6, 7]` because removing this subarray changes the array `[5, 3, 4, 6, 7]` to `[5, 6, 7]` which is strictly increasing.\n\nReturn *the total number of **incremovable** subarrays of* `nums`.\n\n**Note** that an empty array is considered strictly increasing.\n\nA **subarray** is a contiguous non-empty sequence of elements within an array.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: nums = [1,2,3,4]\nOutput: 10\nExplanation: The 10 incremovable subarrays are: [1], [2], [3], [4], [1,2], [2,3], [3,4], [1,2,3], [2,3,4], and [1,2,3,4], because on removing any one of these subarrays nums becomes strictly increasing. Note that you cannot select an empty subarray.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: nums = [6,5,7,8]\nOutput: 7\nExplanation: The 7 incremovable subarrays are: [5], [6], [5,7], [6,5], [5,7,8], [6,5,7] and [6,5,7,8].\nIt can be shown that there are only 7 incremovable subarrays in nums.\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: nums = [8,7,6,6]\nOutput: 3\nExplanation: The 3 incremovable subarrays are: [8,7,6], [7,6,6], and [8,7,6,6]. Note that [8,7] is not an incremovable subarray because after removing [8,7] nums becomes [6,6], which is sorted in ascending order but not strictly increasing.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= nums.length <= 50`\n\n- `1 <= nums[i] <= 50`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/count-the-number-of-incremovable-subarrays-i/","problemName":"Count the Number of Incremovable Subarrays I","problemNumber":2970,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are given a **0-indexed** array of **positive** integers `nums`.\n\nA subarray of `nums` is called **incremovable** if `nums` becomes **strictly increasing** on removing the subarray. For example, the subarray `[3, 4]` is an incremovable subarray of `[5, 3, 4, 6, 7]` because removing this subarray changes the array `[5, 3, 4, 6, 7]` to `[5, 6, 7]` which is strictly increasing.\n\nReturn *the total number of **incremovable** subarrays of* `nums`.\n\n**Note** that an empty array is considered strictly increasing.\n\nA **subarray** is a contiguous non-empty sequence of elements within an array.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: nums = [1,2,3,4]\nOutput: 10\nExplanation: The 10 incremovable subarrays are: [1], [2], [3], [4], [1,2], [2,3], [3,4], [1,2,3], [2,3,4], and [1,2,3,4], because on removing any one of these subarrays nums becomes strictly increasing. Note that you cannot select an empty subarray.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: nums = [6,5,7,8]\nOutput: 7\nExplanation: The 7 incremovable subarrays are: [5], [6], [5,7], [6,5], [5,7,8], [6,5,7] and [6,5,7,8].\nIt can be shown that there are only 7 incremovable subarrays in nums.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: nums = [8,7,6,6]\nOutput: 3\nExplanation: The 3 incremovable subarrays are: [8,7,6], [7,6,6], and [8,7,6,6]. Note that [8,7] is not an incremovable subarray because after removing [8,7] nums becomes [6,6], which is sorted in ascending order but not strictly increasing.","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= nums.length <= 50`\n\n- `1 <= nums[i] <= 50`","type":"text"}],"difficulty":"Easy","examples":[],"paidOnly":false,"problem":"You are given a **0-indexed** array of **positive** integers `nums`.\n\nA subarray of `nums` is called **incremovable** if `nums` becomes **strictly increasing** on removing the subarray. For example, the subarray `[3, 4]` is an incremovable subarray of `[5, 3, 4, 6, 7]` because removing this subarray changes the array `[5, 3, 4, 6, 7]` to `[5, 6, 7]` which is strictly increasing.\n\nReturn *the total number of **incremovable** subarrays of* `nums`.\n\n**Note** that an empty array is considered strictly increasing.\n\nA **subarray** is a contiguous non-empty sequence of elements within an array.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: nums = [1,2,3,4]\nOutput: 10\nExplanation: The 10 incremovable subarrays are: [1], [2], [3], [4], [1,2], [2,3], [3,4], [1,2,3], [2,3,4], and [1,2,3,4], because on removing any one of these subarrays nums becomes strictly increasing. Note that you cannot select an empty subarray.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: nums = [6,5,7,8]\nOutput: 7\nExplanation: The 7 incremovable subarrays are: [5], [6], [5,7], [6,5], [5,7,8], [6,5,7] and [6,5,7,8].\nIt can be shown that there are only 7 incremovable subarrays in nums.\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: nums = [8,7,6,6]\nOutput: 3\nExplanation: The 3 incremovable subarrays are: [8,7,6], [7,6,6], and [8,7,6,6]. Note that [8,7] is not an incremovable subarray because after removing [8,7] nums becomes [6,6], which is sorted in ascending order but not strictly increasing.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= nums.length <= 50`\n\n- `1 <= nums[i] <= 50`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/count-the-number-of-incremovable-subarrays-i/","problemName":"Count the Number of Incremovable Subarrays I","problemNumber":2970,"problemSlug":"count-the-number-of-incremovable-subarrays-i","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":2970,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Array","Greedy","Sorting","Prefix Sum"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are given an array of **positive** integers `nums` of length `n`.\n\nA **polygon** is a closed plane figure that has at least `3` sides. The **longest side** of a polygon is **smaller** than the sum of its other sides.\n\nConversely, if you have `k` (`k >= 3`) **positive** real numbers `a1`, `a2`, `a3`, ..., `ak` where `a1 <= a2 <= a3 <= ... <= ak` **and** `a1 + a2 + a3 + ... + ak-1 > ak`, then there **always** exists a polygon with `k` sides whose lengths are `a1`, `a2`, `a3`, ..., `ak`.\n\nThe **perimeter** of a polygon is the sum of lengths of its sides.\n\nReturn *the **largest** possible **perimeter** of a **polygon** whose sides can be formed from* `nums`, *or* `-1` *if it is not possible to create a polygon*.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: nums = [5,5,5]\nOutput: 15\nExplanation: The only possible polygon that can be made from nums has 3 sides: 5, 5, and 5. The perimeter is 5 + 5 + 5 = 15.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: nums = [1,12,1,2,5,50,3]\nOutput: 12\nExplanation: The polygon with the largest perimeter which can be made from nums has 5 sides: 1, 1, 2, 3, and 5. The perimeter is 1 + 1 + 2 + 3 + 5 = 12.\nWe cannot have a polygon with either 12 or 50 as the longest side because it is not possible to include 2 or more smaller sides that have a greater sum than either of them.\nIt can be shown that the largest possible perimeter is 12.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: nums = [5,5,50]\nOutput: -1\nExplanation: There is no possible way to form a polygon from nums, as a polygon has at least 3 sides and 50 > 5 + 5.","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `3 <= n <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= nums[i] <= 10⁹`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Greedy","Sorting","Prefix Sum"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"You are given an array of **positive** integers `nums` of length `n`.\n\nA **polygon** is a closed plane figure that has at least `3` sides. The **longest side** of a polygon is **smaller** than the sum of its other sides.\n\nConversely, if you have `k` (`k >= 3`) **positive** real numbers `a1`, `a2`, `a3`, ..., `ak` where `a1 <= a2 <= a3 <= ... <= ak` **and** `a1 + a2 + a3 + ... + ak-1 > ak`, then there **always** exists a polygon with `k` sides whose lengths are `a1`, `a2`, `a3`, ..., `ak`.\n\nThe **perimeter** of a polygon is the sum of lengths of its sides.\n\nReturn *the **largest** possible **perimeter** of a **polygon** whose sides can be formed from* `nums`, *or* `-1` *if it is not possible to create a polygon*.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: nums = [5,5,5]\nOutput: 15\nExplanation: The only possible polygon that can be made from nums has 3 sides: 5, 5, and 5. The perimeter is 5 + 5 + 5 = 15.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: nums = [1,12,1,2,5,50,3]\nOutput: 12\nExplanation: The polygon with the largest perimeter which can be made from nums has 5 sides: 1, 1, 2, 3, and 5. The perimeter is 1 + 1 + 2 + 3 + 5 = 12.\nWe cannot have a polygon with either 12 or 50 as the longest side because it is not possible to include 2 or more smaller sides that have a greater sum than either of them.\nIt can be shown that the largest possible perimeter is 12.\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: nums = [5,5,50]\nOutput: -1\nExplanation: There is no possible way to form a polygon from nums, as a polygon has at least 3 sides and 50 > 5 + 5.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `3 <= n <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= nums[i] <= 10⁹`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/find-polygon-with-the-largest-perimeter/","problemName":"Find Polygon With the Largest Perimeter","problemNumber":2971,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are given an array of **positive** integers `nums` of length `n`.\n\nA **polygon** is a closed plane figure that has at least `3` sides. The **longest side** of a polygon is **smaller** than the sum of its other sides.\n\nConversely, if you have `k` (`k >= 3`) **positive** real numbers `a1`, `a2`, `a3`, ..., `ak` where `a1 <= a2 <= a3 <= ... <= ak` **and** `a1 + a2 + a3 + ... + ak-1 > ak`, then there **always** exists a polygon with `k` sides whose lengths are `a1`, `a2`, `a3`, ..., `ak`.\n\nThe **perimeter** of a polygon is the sum of lengths of its sides.\n\nReturn *the **largest** possible **perimeter** of a **polygon** whose sides can be formed from* `nums`, *or* `-1` *if it is not possible to create a polygon*.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":